Analytical Lasso solution with Helmert design matrix¶

Key observation is that the design matrix (first \(p\) columns of a Helmert matrix) has orthonormal columns. Therefore

It is immediate that the minimizer is given by \(\hat \beta_1(\lambda) = y^T x_{\cdot 1}\) and \(\hat \beta_j(\lambda) = ST(y^T x_{\cdot j}, \lambda)\) for \(j=2,\ldots,p\).

Now let's generate design matrix and responses.

In [2]:
include("hw7.jl")
# design matrix is transpose of the Helmert matrix
srand(2015790003)
n = 10000
p = 1000
H = helmert(n)'
X = H[:, 1:p]
println(countnz(X) / length(X)) # sparsity
 = zeros(size(X, 2))
k = 5 # number of non-zeros
[1:k] = 1:k
y = X *  + randn(n)
penidx = [false, trues(size(X, 2) - 1)]

# set up grid and compute the analytical solution
list = convert(Vector{Float64}, 0.0:0.6:6.0)
hattrue = zeros(size(X, 2), length(list))
xty = X' * y
for i = 1:length(list)
    hattrue[:, i] = copysign(max(abs(xty) - list[i], 0.0), xty)
    hattrue[1, i] = xty[1]
end

#
# This function fits lasso regression with responses y and design matrix X.
# The logical vector penidx indiciates which predictors are penalized.
#
function lsqlassopath(y::Vector{Float64}, X::Matrix{Float64},
                      grid::Vector{Float64}=[0.0];
                      algo::String="Convex.jl", maxiter::Int=1000,
                      objtol::Float64=1e-4, penidx::BitArray{1}=trues(size(X, 2)))

  # allocate space for solution
  p = size(X, 2)
  ngrid = length(grid)
  hat = zeros(p, ngrid)

  # pre-compute sum-of-squares of columns of X
  xjnrm2 = squeeze(sumabs2(X, 1), 1)

  # path following from large 
  if all(penidx)
    for i = ngrid:-1:1
       = grid[i]
      if i == ngrid
        # cold start
        hat[:, i] = lsqlasso(y, X, ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
                              objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2)
      else
        # warm start
        hat[:, i] = lsqlasso(y, X, ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
                              objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2, 0=hat[:, i+1])
      end
    end
  else
    X1 = X[:, !penidx] # unpenalized predictors
    X2 = X[:, penidx]  # penalized predictors
    X1U, X1, X1V = svd(X1, thin=true)
    ywork = y - X1U * (X1U' * y)
    Xwork = X2 - X1U * (X1U' * X2)
    for i = ngrid:-1:1
       = grid[i]
      if i == ngrid
        # cold start
        hat[penidx, i] = lsqlasso(ywork, Xwork, ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
                                   objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2[penidx])
      else
        # warm start
        #hat[penidx, i] = lsqlasso(ywork, Xwork, ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
        #                           objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2[penidx],
        #                           0=hat[penidx, i+1])
        hat[penidx, i] = lsqlasso(ywork, Xwork, ; algo=algo, maxiter=maxiter,
                                   objtol=objtol, xjnrm2=xjnrm2[penidx])
      end
      hat[!penidx, i] = X1V * ((X1U' * (y - X2 * hat[penidx, i])) ./ X1)
    end
  end

  return hat
end

#
# This function fits lasso regression with responses y and design matrix X.
# This function assumes all predictors are penalized. If X = (X1, X2), where
# X1 is not penalized, we can project y and X2 to the null space of X', then
# call this function.
#
function lsqlasso(y::Vector{Float64}, X::Matrix{Float64}, ::Float64=0.0;
                  algo::String="Convex.jl",
                  0::Vector{Float64}=zeros(size(X, 2)),
                  maxiter::Int=1000, objtol::Float64=1e-4,
                  xjnrm2::Vector{Float64}=sumabs2(X, 1))

  # Retrieve dimensions
  n, p = size(X)

  if algo == "Convex.jl"

    # Create optimization variables
    hat = Convex.Variable(size(X, 2))
    # Set up optmization problem
    problem = Convex.minimize(0.5 * Convex.sum_squares(y - X * hat)
                              +  * Convex.norm(hat, 1))
    # Solve the problem
    Convex.solve!(problem)
    # Return
    hat.value

  elseif algo == "CD"

    # initial point
    hat = copy(0)
    # resid = y - X * hat
    resid = copy(y)
    BLAS.gemv!('N', -1.0, X, hat, 1.0, resid)
    # Objective value at initial point
    objval = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) +  * sumabs(hat)
    # Pointer to residual vector
    ptrres = pointer(resid)
    ptrinc = n * sizeof(Float64) # increment for pointer
    # Coordinate descent (CD) loop
    for iter = 1:maxiter
      # Renew the pointer to X[1, 1]
      ptrxj = pointer(X)
      # Update j
      for j = 1:p
        # dot function is ~10 times slower than BLAS; pointer helps a lot!
        #tmp = hat[j] + dot(X[:, j], resid) / xjnrm2[j]
        #tmp = hat[j] + BLAS.dot(n, X[:, j], 1, resid, 1) / xjnrm2[j]
        # looping is about same speed as BLAS
        # tmp = 0.0
        #@simd for i = 1:n
        #  @inbounds tmp += X[i, j] * resid[i]
        #end
        #tmp /= xjnrm2[j]
        #tmp += hat[j]
        # BLAS is fastest
        tmp = hat[j] + BLAS.dot(n, ptrxj, 1, ptrres, 1) / xjnrm2[j]
        # Soft-thresholding
        tmp = copysign(max(abs(tmp) -  / xjnrm2[j], 0.0), tmp)
        jdiff = hat[j] - tmp # difference from last iterate
        if abs(jdiff) > 1e-16
          # Update residual
          BLAS.axpy!(n, jdiff, ptrxj, 1, ptrres, 1)
        end
        hat[j] = tmp
        # Advance pointer to next column of X
        ptrxj += ptrinc
      end
      # Check convergence criterion
      objvalold = objval
      objval = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) +  * sumabs(hat)
      if abs(objvalold - objval) < objtol * (abs(objvalold) + 1.0)
        break
      end
    end
    # return
    hat

  elseif algo == "ISTA"

    # initial point
    hat = copy(0)
    resid = y - X * hat # use axpy?
    objval = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) +  * sumabs(hat)
    # initial step length and line search max iteration
    s::Float64 = 1.0
    #s = eigs(X' * X; nev=1, maxiter=5, ritzvec=false, which=:LM)[1][1]
    lsmaxiter::Int = 10
    # allocate intermediate variable
    new = zeros(hat)
    grad = zeros(hat)
    for iter = 1:maxiter
      # Update gradient
      # grad = - X' * resid
      BLAS.gemv!('T', -1.0, X, resid, 0.0, grad)
      # Line search loop
      for lsiter = 1:lsmaxiter
        new = hat - s * grad # use BLAS
        # Soft-thresholding
        @simd for j = 1:p
          @inbounds new[j] = copysign(max(abs(new[j]) - s * , 0.0), new[j])
        end
        residnew = y - X * new # use BLAS
        objnew = 0.5 * sumabs2(residnew) #+  * sumabs(new)
        # TODO: change this to looping
        surnew = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) + dot(new - hat, grad) +
          0.5 / s * sumabs2(new - hat) #+  * sumabs(new)
        if objnew <= surnew
          hat = copy(new)
          resid = copy(residnew)
          break
        else
          s /= 2.0
        end
      end
      # Check convergence criterion
      objvalold = objval
      objval = 0.5 * sumabs2(resid) +  * sumabs(hat)
      if abs(objvalold - objval) < objtol * (abs(objvalold) + 1.0)
        break
      end
    end
    # return
    hat

  end

end

#
# This function generates the Helmert matrix of size n.
#
function helmert(n::Int)

  H = zeros(n, n)
  H[:, 1] = 1 / sqrt(n)
  for j = 2:n
    H[1:j-1, j] = 1 / sqrt(j * (j - 1))
    H[j, j] = - (j - 1) / sqrt(j * (j - 1))
  end
  H = H'

end
